Biodiversity Loss Reduces Global Terrestrial Carbon Storage
Sarah R. Weiskopf, Forest Isbell, Maria Isabel Arce-Plata, Moreno Di Marco, Mike Harfoot, Justin Johnson, Susannah B. Lerman, Brian W. Miller, Toni Lyn Morelli, Akira S. Mori, Ensheng Weng & Simon Ferrier
Natural ecosystems store large amounts of carbon globally, as organisms absorb carbon from the atmosphere to build large, long-lasting, or slow-decaying structures such as tree bark or root systems — but an ecosystem's carbon sequestration potential is tightly linked to its biological diversity. The core finding is alarming: biodiversity declines from climate and land use change could lead to a global loss of between 7.44–103.14 PgC under a global sustainability scenario and 10.87–145.95 PgC under a fossil-fueled development scenario. NASA GISS
This reveals a dangerous cycle: higher levels of climate change lead to greater biodiversity loss, which in turn leads to greater carbon emissions and ultimately more climate change. Experts@Minnesota
The policy implication is direct: achieving Sustainable Development Goal 15 (Life on Land) can contribute to achieving Goal 13 (Climate Action) — and additional mitigation measures may be needed to meet Paris Agreement expectations even if current emission reduction targets are met. 
